<p>
  More recently, Wagner’s lab found that GDF11 also <a href="http://www.sciencemag.org/content/344/6184/649.abstract">improves muscle healing, endurance, and overall strength in older mice</a>. Harvard neuroscientist Lee Rubin’s lab found that GDF11 has a similar effect on mouse brains, encouraging new blood vessel and olfactory neuron growth (i.e. the old mice could smell better with young blood). In typical fashion, Harvard is currently attempting to patent the naturally occuring GDF11. But the effects aren't limited to the single growth factor; researchers at Stanford and UCSF found that injecting blood plasma from young to old mice <a href="http://www.nature.com/nm/journal/vaop/ncurrent/full/nm.3569.html">improved connections between hippocampal neurons</a>, which are responsible for memory. If these effects carry over to humans, we could see a wonder drug for cardiovascular disease, Alzheimer's, and general shittiness that comes from old-age. All we need is the blood of our young.
</p>